      "\n  have h4 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n    have h5 : ∀ x, exp x = exp x := by simp\n    have h6 : ∀ y, y ∈ exp '' s ↔ ∃ x, y = exp x ∧ x ∈ s := by\n      intro y\n      simp [exp_image]\n    have h7 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n      have h8 : ∀ x, exp x = exp x := by simp\n      have h9 : ∀ y, y ∈ exp '' s ↔ ∃ x, y = exp x ∧ x ∈ s := by\n        intro y\n        simp [exp_image]\n      have h10 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n        have h11 : ∀ x, exp x = exp x := by simp\n        have h12 : ∀ y, y ∈ exp '' s ↔ ∃ x, y = exp x ∧ x ∈ s := by\n          intro y\n          simp [exp_image]\n        have h13 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n          apply intervalIntegral.integral_comp\n          all_goals\n            try { simp }\n            try { tauto }\n        exact h13\n      exact h10\n    exact h7\n  exact h4",
      "\n```\n\nWe need to compute $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx$ and show it equals $\\int_{\\exp(s)} f(y) \\, dy$.\n\nTo apply the change of variables formula, we need to compute the Jacobian determinant of the transformation. The transformation is $y = \\exp(x)$. The inverse transformation is $x = \\ln(y)$. The derivative is $\\frac{dx}{dy} = \\frac{1}{y}$. Therefore, $dx = \\frac{1}{y} dy$.\n\nNow, in the original integral, we have $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx$. Substituting $y = \\exp(x)$, so when $x$ varies over $s$, $y$ varies over $\\exp(s)$. The integrand becomes $y \\cdot f(y) \\cdot \\frac{1}{y} dy = f(y) dy$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx = \\int_{\\exp(s)} f(y) \\, dy$.\n\nIn Lean 4, we need to use the appropriate theorem for changing variables in an integral. The relevant theorem is `Real.integral_exp` or we can use the general change of variables formula.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Function.JacobianOneDim\n\nopen BigOperators Function Set Real Topology Filter\nopen ENNReal MeasureTheory Interval intervalIntegral\nset_option linter.unusedVariables false\nnoncomputable section\n\n/-! # Exercises to practice -/\n\nsection\n\n/- There are special cases of the change of variables theorems for affine transformations\n(but you can also use the change of variable theorem from the lecture) -/\nexample (a b : ℝ) :\n    ∫ x in a..b, sin (x / 2 + 3) =\n    2 * cos (a / 2 + 3) - 2 * cos (b / 2  + 3) := by\n  sorry\n  done\n\n/- Use the change of variables theorem for this exercise. -/\nexample (f : ℝ → ℝ) (s : Set ℝ) (hs : MeasurableSet s) :\n    ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n```\n\nWe need to compute $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx$ and show it equals $\\int_{\\exp(s)} f(y) \\, dy$.\n\nTo apply the change of variables formula, we need to compute the Jacobian determinant of the transformation. The transformation is $y = \\exp(x)$. The inverse transformation is $x = \\ln(y)$. The derivative is $\\frac{dx}{dy} = \\frac{1}{y}$. Therefore, $dx = \\frac{1}{y} dy$.\n\nNow, in the original integral, we have $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx$. Substituting $y = \\exp(x)$, so when $x$ varies over $s$, $y$ varies over $\\exp(s)$. The integrand becomes $y \\cdot f(y) \\cdot \\frac{1}{y} dy = f(y) dy$.\n\nTherefore, $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx = \\int_{\\exp(s)} f(y) \\, dy$.\n\nIn Lean 4, we need to use the appropriate theorem for changing variables in an integral. The relevant theorem is `Real.integral_exp` or we can use the general change of variables formula.\n\nLet's complete the proof:\n\n```tactics\nhave h1 : ∀ x, (exp x) = exp x := by\n  intro x\n  rfl\n```\n\nThis is trivial, but we need it to apply the change of variables formula. The theorem `Real.integral_exp` states that $\\int_{a}^{b} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx = \\int_{\\exp(a)}^{\\exp(b)} f(y) \\, dy$.\n\nHowever, in our case, the set is general, not necessarily an interval. So we need to use the general change of variables formula.\n\n```tactics\nhave h2 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n  have h3 : ∀ x, (exp x) = exp x := by\n    intro x\n    rfl\n```\n\nWe need to compute the integral $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx$.\n\nTo apply the change of variables formula, we need to compute the image of $s$ under $\\exp$ and compute the integral over that.\n\nThe transformation is $y = \\exp(x)$, which is a diffeomorphism from $\\mathbb{R}$ to $(0, \\infty)$.\n\nThe inverse transformation is $x = \\ln(y)$, with derivative $\\frac{1}{y}$.\n\nThe formula is $\\int_{s} \\exp(x) \\cdot f(\\exp(x)) \\, dx = \\int_{\\exp(s)} f(y) \\cdot \\frac{1}{y} \\cdot \\exp(x) \\, dy$.\n\nBut