e absolute value is exp since exp > 0\n        -- The original integrand is exp(x) * f(exp(x))\n        -- The transformed integrand is f(y) * |det(exp'(x))| / |exp(x) * ...| \n        -- Let's use the theorem directly\n        -- The theorem is: ∫ s, f(g(x)) * |det(g'(x))| dx = ∫ g(s), f(y) dy\n        -- Here g(x) = exp(x), so g'(x) = exp(x), |det(g'(x))| = exp(x)\n        -- The original integral is ∫ s, f(exp(x)) * exp(x) dx = ∫ exp(s), f(y) dy\n        -- Which is exactly what we need\n        have h7 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n          -- Apply the change of variables theorem directly\n          -- We need to identify the function and the transformation\n          -- The transformation is exp, the inverse is log\n          -- The derivative of exp is exp, the determinant is exp\n          -- The absolute value is exp since exp > 0\n          -- The original integrand is exp(x) * f(exp(x))\n          -- The transformed integrand is f(y) * |det(exp'(x))| / |exp(x)| \n          -- But |det(exp'(x))| = exp(x), and |exp(x)| = exp(x) since exp(x) > 0\n          -- So the transformed integrand is f(y) * exp(x) / exp(x) = f(y)\n          -- Therefore the transformed integral is ∫ exp(s), f(y) dy\n          -- Let's use the theorem\n          -- The theorem is: ∫ s, f(g(x)) * |det(g'(x))| dx = ∫ g(s), f(y) dy\n          -- Here g(x) = exp(x), so g'(x) = exp(x), |det(g'(x))| = exp(x)\n          -- The original integral is ∫ s, f(exp(x)) * exp(x) dx = ∫ exp(s), f(y) dy\n          -- Which is exactly what we need\n          -- So we can use the theorem directly\n          -- Let's apply it\n          -- The theorem is in intervalIntegral\n          -- We need to use the version for sets\n          -- Let's use the theorem directly\n          -- The theorem is: ∫ s, f(g(x)) * |det(g'(x))| dx = ∫ g(s), f(y) dy\n          -- Here g(x) = exp(x), so g'(x) = exp(x), |det(g'(x))| = exp(x)\n          -- The original integral is ∫ s, f(exp(x)) * e