      "\n  have h1 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n```\n\nTo apply the change of variables theorem, we need to identify the transformation and compute the determinant of the Jacobian.\n\nThe transformation is y = exp(x). Therefore:\nx = log(y)\nThe derivative dx/dy = 1/y\nThe determinant of the Jacobian is |1/y| = 1/y since y > 0 (as exp(x) > 0)\n\nThe original integrand is exp x * f (exp x) dx\nThe transformed integrand is f y dy\n\nLet's see how these are related:\nexp x * f (exp x) dx = exp x * f (exp x) * dx\n= exp x * f (exp x) * (1/y) dy\n= exp x * f (exp x) * (1/exp x) dy\n= f (exp x) dy\n= f y dy\n\nSo the original integrand is transformed to f y dy, which is exactly the integrand in the transformed integral. Therefore, we can apply the change of variables theorem.\n\nIn Lean, we can use `intervalIntegral.integral_comp`.\n\n```tactics\n    have h2 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n      have h3 : ∫ x in s, exp x * f (exp x) = ∫ y in exp '' s, f y := by\n        have h4 : ∀ x : ℝ, exp x * f (exp x) = f (exp x) * (1 / (exp x) ) * (exp x) := by\n          intro x\n          have h5 : exp x > 0 := by positivity\n          field_simp\n          <;> ring\n```\n\nWait, this is still not right. Let's think. The original integrand is exp x * f (exp x) dx. The transformation is y = exp(x). Therefore:\nexp x = y\nf (exp x) = f y\ndx = (1/y) dy\nTherefore, the integrand becomes:\nexp x * f (exp x) * dx = y * f y * (1/y) dy = f y dy\n\nSo the original integrand is transformed to f y dy, which is exactly the integrand in the transformed integral. Therefore, we need to use the change of variables theorem.\n\nIn Lean, the relevant lemma is `intervalIntegral.integral_comp`.\n\n```tactics\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.SpecialFunctions.Integrals.Basic\nimport Mathlib.RingTheory.Real.Irrational\nimport Mathlib.Analysis.Convolution\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Integral.Prod\nimport Mathlib.MeasureTheory.Function.JacobianOneDim\n\