We need to show that $\int_{s} e^{x} \cdot f(e^{x}) \, dx = \int_{\exp(s)} f(y) \, dy$.

In calculus, we would use the substitution $y = e^{x}$, so $dy = e^{x} \, dx$, which gives $dx = \frac{dy}{y}$. Then the left integral becomes $\int_{\exp(s)} y \cdot f(y) \cdot \frac{1}{y} \, dy = \int_{\exp(s)} f(y) \, dy$, which is the right side.

